to
understand,"
said
Sir
Thomas,
after
a
few
moments'
silence,
"that
you
mean
to
refuse
Mr.
Crawford?"
"Yes,
sir."
"Refuse
him?"
"Yes,
sir."
"Refuse
Mr.
Crawford!
Upon
what
plea?
For
what
reason?"
"I
I
cannot
like
him,
sir,
well
enough
to
marry
him."
"This
is
very
strange!"
said
Sir
Thomas,
in
a
voice
of
calm
displeasure.
"There
is
something
in
this
which
my
comprehension
does
not
reach.
Here
is
a
young
man
wishing
to
pay
his
addresses
to
you,
with
everything
to
recommend
him:
not
