together,
even
if
I
could
like
him.
There
never
were
two
people
more
dissimilar.
We
have
not
one
taste
in
common.
We
should
be
miserable."
"You
are
mistaken,
Fanny.
The
dissimilarity
is
not
so
strong.
You
are
quite
enough
alike.
You
have
tastes
in
common.
You
have
moral
and
literary
tastes
in
common.
You
have
both
warm
hearts
and
benevolent
feelings;
and,
Fanny,
who
that
heard
him
read,
and
saw
you
listen
to
Shakespeare
the
other
