to
be
grave
or
to
be
gay.
Some
opposition
here
is,
I
am
thoroughly
convinced,
friendly
to
matrimonial
happiness.
I
exclude
extremes,
of
course;
and
a
very
close
resemblance
in
all
those
points
would
be
the
likeliest
way
to
produce
an
extreme.
A
counteraction,
gentle
and
continual,
is
the
best
safeguard
of
manners
and
conduct."
Full
well
could
Fanny
guess
where
his
thoughts
were
now:
Miss
Crawford's
power
was
all
returning.
He
had
been
speaking
of
her
cheerfully
from
the
hour
of
his
coming
home.
His
avoiding
her
was
quite
at
