of
others
than
formerly.
And,
if
in
little
things,
must
it
not
be
so
in
great?
So
anxious
for
her
health
and
comfort,
so
very
feeling
as
he
now
expressed
himself,
and
really
seemed,
might
not
it
be
fairly
supposed
that
he
would
not
much
longer
persevere
in
a
suit
so
distressing
to
her?
It
was
presumed
that
Mr.
Crawford
was
travelling
back,
to
London,
on
the
morrow,
for
nothing
more
was
seen
of
him
at
Mr.
Price's;
and
two
days
afterwards,
it
was
a
fact
ascertained
to
Fanny
by
the
following
letter
from
his
sister,
opened
and
read
by
her,
on
another
account,
with
the
most
