of
not
appearing
ignorant,
as,
with
a
good
clear
understanding,
made
her
a
most
attentive,
profitable,
thankful
pupil.
Fanny
was
her
oracle.
Fanny's
explanations
and
remarks
were
a
most
important
addition
to
every
essay,
or
every
chapter
of
history.
What
Fanny
told
her
of
former
times
dwelt
more
on
her
mind
than
the
pages
of
Goldsmith;
and
she
paid
her
sister
the
compliment
of
preferring
her
style
to
that
of
any
printed
author.
The
early
habit
of
reading
was
wanting.
Their
