behind
her,
there
might
have
been
danger
of
his
learning
almost
to
approve
the
evil
which
produced
such
a
good.
She
was
regretted
by
no
one
at
Mansfield.
She
had
never
been
able
to
attach
even
those
she
loved
best;
and
since
Mrs.
Rushworth's
elopement,
her
temper
had
been
in
a
state
of
such
irritation
as
to
make
her
everywhere
tormenting.
Not
even
Fanny
had
tears
for
aunt
Norris,
not
even
when
she
was
gone
for
ever.
That
Julia
escaped
better
than
Maria
was
owing,
in
some
