of
gallantry,
of
flirtation,
which
bounded
his
views;
but
in
triumphing
over
the
discretion
which,
though
beginning
in
anger,
might
have
saved
them
both,
he
had
put
himself
in
the
power
of
feelings
on
her
side
more
strong
than
he
had
supposed.
She
loved
him;
there
was
no
withdrawing
attentions
avowedly
dear
to
her.
He
was
entangled
by
his
own
vanity,
with
as
little
excuse
of
love
as
possible,
and
without
the
smallest
inconstancy
of
mind
towards
her
cousin.
To
keep
Fanny
and
the
Bertrams
from
a
knowledge
of
what
was
passing
became
his
first
