of
disgrace,
should
in
a
just
measure
attend
his
share
of
the
offence
is,
we
know,
not
one
of
the
barriers
which
society
gives
to
virtue.
In
this
world
the
penalty
is
less
equal
than
could
be
wished;
but
without
presuming
to
look
forward
to
a
juster
appointment
hereafter,
we
may
fairly
consider
a
man
of
sense,
like
Henry
Crawford,
to
be
providing
for
himself
no
small
portion
of
vexation
and
