her
head.
Edmund
had
greatly
the
advantage
of
her
in
this
respect.
He
had
not
to
wait
and
wish
with
vacant
affections
for
an
object
worthy
to
succeed
her
in
them.
Scarcely
had
he
done
regretting
Mary
Crawford,
and
observing
