must
vary
much
as
to
time
in
different
people.
I
only
entreat
everybody
to
believe
that
exactly
at
the
time
when
it
was
quite
natural
that
it
should
be
so,
and
not
a
week
earlier,
Edmund
did
cease
to
care
about
Miss
Crawford,
and
became
as
anxious
to
marry
Fanny
as
Fanny
herself
could
desire.
With
such
a
regard
for
her,
indeed,
as
his
had
long
been,
a
